<TEXT>
a senior military commander saturday 
ordered troops to guard against possible terrorist attacks at us 
military bases on the third anniversary of the american air raid in 
libya 
maj gen ramon montano chief of the philippine constabulary 
gave the order in a radio message to field units stationed near 
us military bases 
montano said american authorities advised that terrorist groups 
might attack clark air base subic bay naval base and four other 
smaller military installations to mark the april 15 1986 us air 
raid on tripoli and benghazi libya he told military commanders to 
institute appropriate security measures around the american 
facilities 
at least 41 people were killed during the air raids on libya 
and two american airmen died when their plane was shot down over 
tripoli the attack was in retaliation for the april 5 1986 
bombing of a discoteque in west berlin that killed two people 
including a us serviceman and wounded 200 
montano said last weeks attack by communist new peoples army 
rebels on a us communications station in northern benguet 
province and the discovery of a wire bomb near clark have caused 
the us embassy concern 
the rebels destroyed a giant antenna and three utility poles in 
the attack on the station rebels said the attack was a response to 
the escalating us military intervention in the country there 
were no injuries and the site remained operational rebels did not 
claim responsibility for the wire bomb 
the bombing was the first attack on a us facility or us 
personnel since october 1987 when rebels killed three americans 
and a filipino near clark 
the rebels have been fighting the government for 20 years to 
establish a communist state in the philippines 
