<TEXT>
tamil rebels offered saturday to hold 
talks with the government on ending their war for independence and 
president ranasinghe premadasa responded by asking the group to 
send their leaders to meet with him 
the tamil offer came hours after an ambush blamed on the rebels 
left 21 soldiers dead the attack brought to 79 the number of 
people killed in three days of violence blamed on rebels 
a spokesman for the liberation tigers of tamil eelam the 
largest and most powerful tamil rebel group said saturday the 
group sent a letter to premadasa offering to hold talks 
the last talks between the tigers and the government were held 
in 1985 in thimpu bhutan the negotiations ended in failure 
presidential press secretary evans cooray told the associated 
press a message already has been sent to anton balasingham 
political leader of the tamil tigers asking him to choose 
representatives for the talks 
cooray said a message signed by premadasa secretary kha 
wijayadasa was sent to balasingham that read your message to 
have a dialogue with the president of sri lanka is very much 
appreciated 
he has instructed me to request you to nominate accredited 
representatives to discuss necessary arrangements to facilitate the 
dialogue anywhere in sri lanka 
also sunday a tiger leader in colombo said he met with 
premadasa at anuradhapura 103 miles north of colombo and 
personally conveyed the tiger message to premadasa 
the leader who spoke on condition of anonymity said premadasa 
was anxious to begin the talks 
the movement toward talks comes after three days of heavy 
bloodshed blamed on the rebels 
saturdays jungle ambush occurred near parakramapura in weli oya 
district where soldiers were guarding sinhalese laborers clearing 
the forest military officials in colombo said 
at least 21 soldiers were killed and four laborers were 
critically injured in the fighting the officials said speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the village is about 150 miles northeast of colombo 
on friday at least 12 people were killed and 18 others injured 
in the tamildominated town of jaffna 180 miles north of colombo 
when a car bomb exploded near the towns university 
military officials in colombo said the bomb was intended for 
soldiers in a small camp nearby and exploded prematurely 
on thursday a car bomb in the port city of trincomalee killed 
45 people mostly members of the sinhalese ethnic majority 
that explosion came a day after security forces began a weeklong 
unilateral ceasefire in an effort to persuade both rebels of the 
tamil minority and militant members of the sinhalese majority to 
stop fighting 
both groups of radicals rejected the ceasefire proposal 
tamil separatists launched their bloody battle in 1983 
attacking the sinhalesedominated governments troops and sinhalese 
civilians government efforts to pacify the tamil militants by 
offering them a measure of autonomy in 1987 backfired 
the tigers rejected the overtures and militant sinhalese 
embarked on their own campaign of assassinations against the 
government saying too many concessions were being offered the 
tamils 
sinhalese who are mostly buddhists comprise 75 percent of sri 
lankas 16 million people tamils who are mostly hindus account 
for 18 percent moslems comprise most other people on the island 
formerly known as ceylon 
india the regions biggest military power tried to help end 
sri lankas internal strife through a 1987 peace pact under the 
pact india dispatched peacekeeping troops prompted by the 
political sympathies of its own tamil minority of 60 million 
more than 12500 people including at least 800 indian soldiers 
have died in the war 
